1
00:00:00,200 --> 00:00:11,717
This walkthrough builds an interactive account-risk assistant with Oracle AI Database, A G U I, A two U I, the Oracle Database M C P Java Toolkit, and an optional M C P App.

2
00:00:11,717 --> 00:00:15,443
The result is a governed workflow, not just a text answer.

3
00:00:15,843 --> 00:00:20,179
The browser receives streamed agent events and declarative interface updates.

4
00:00:20,179 --> 00:00:24,950
The Java orchestration service owns the run, validation, and human approval.

5
00:00:24,950 --> 00:00:31,021
Narrow tools reach Oracle AI Database, which remains the authoritative data and transaction layer.

6
00:00:31,421 --> 00:00:37,504
The agent service emits standard A G U I run, text, tool-call, and state events over server-sent events.

7
00:00:37,504 --> 00:00:39,532
Database failures become a run error.

8
00:00:39,532 --> 00:00:45,277
A two U I envelopes travel inside a standard custom event named a two U I message.

9
00:00:45,677 --> 00:00:54,804
The browser accepts only A two U I version zero point nine point one, the expected surface and catalog, and a small component allowlist.

10
00:00:54,804 --> 00:01:02,030
Generated values enter the page as text, so an agent cannot inject executable H T M L or JavaScript.

11
00:01:02,430 --> 00:01:07,206
The runnable path uses Oracle Universal Connection Pool against the financial database.

12
00:01:07,206 --> 00:01:16,759
It validates connections on borrow, bounds the pool and wait time, binds the minimum risk score, and limits rows before returning governed account data.

13
00:01:17,159 --> 00:01:22,046
Oracle AI Database stores the accounts, risk evidence, and follow-up actions.

14
00:01:22,046 --> 00:01:29,599
The narrow stored procedure validates inputs, locks the selected account, inserts one action, and returns its identifier.

15
00:01:29,599 --> 00:01:33,154
The Java caller explicitly commits or rolls back.

16
00:01:33,554 --> 00:01:39,968
The Oracle Database M C P Java Toolkit configuration exposes bounded business reads, not unrestricted SQL.

17
00:01:39,968 --> 00:01:45,580
Every user value is a bind, and only the account-risk toolset should be enabled.

18
00:01:45,580 --> 00:01:49,588
The transactional write is represented by a narrow extension contract.

19
00:01:49,988 --> 00:01:56,152
For compatible conversational hosts, the optional M C P App registers a sandboxed dashboard resource.

20
00:01:56,152 --> 00:02:04,371
Structured account data crosses the host bridge, while the dashboard never receives database credentials and never connects directly to Oracle.

21
00:02:04,771 --> 00:02:09,182
In the live application, the user sets a risk threshold and row limit.

22
00:02:09,182 --> 00:02:18,683
The A G U I event rail shows the run and database tool activity, while A two U I renders selectable account cards, risk explanations, and approval controls.

23
00:02:19,083 --> 00:02:24,809
Approval is bound to the actor, returned account set, and a short-lived single-use identifier.

24
00:02:24,809 --> 00:02:28,899
Approve calls the procedure and displays the committed action identifier.

25
00:02:28,899 --> 00:02:32,580
Cancel consumes the approval without creating a database action.

26
00:02:32,980 --> 00:02:49,999
Each component keeps one clear responsibility: A G U I streams, A two U I describes trusted controls, M C P Apps add rich sandboxed experiences, narrow M C P tools expose business capabilities, and Oracle AI Database governs the data and transaction.

